{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480073"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"9"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/9"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.02,0.39,0.06,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101967"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84425"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2576"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"77"},{"type":"contributions","id":"511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35810"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101967"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man is transferred to a general medical ward after 48 hours in the Intensive Care Unit. His primary diagnosis was a bleeding gastric ulcer which was successfully treated endoscopically and with high dose intravenous pantoprazole. The day after his transfer he experiences some breathlessness, complains of right sided chest pain, and has a productive cough with yellow sputum. He has no medical history, no allergies, and has no recent antibiotic use. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, pulse 100/min, temperature 38.2C, and respiratory rate 21/min and oxygen saturations 94% on room air. A nasal swab, blood cultures and sputum culture are arranged. A chest X-ray demonstrates a well-defined opacity in the right lower zone, blunting of the right costophrenic angle, and an obscured right heart border.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous benzylpenicillin and oral doxycycline","Oral metronidazole","Intravenous piperacillin/tazobactam","Intravenous vancomycin","Oral amoxicillin/clavulanic acid"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute infective respiratory symptoms supported by findings of an opacity on his chest X-ray. He has been hospitalised for \u0026gt;48 hours thus his presentation is most consistent with hospital-acquired pneumonia (HAP). In all cases of hospital-acquired pneumonia, the risk of multidrug-resistant (MDR) organisms must be assessed. As this man was in a high-risk ward (ICU/HDU) for a relatively short time (\u0026lt;5 days) and has not recently been on antibiotic therapy, he is unlikely to have a MDR infection. Based on his clinical picture, this would likely be categorised as low-moderate severity HAP, due to the absence of hypotension, signs of sepsis, need for intubation and rapid deterioration. Thus, empirical therapy would aim to target Streptococcus pneumoniae and aerobic Gram-negative bacilli. Where tolerated, oral therapy is typically preferred over enteral (e.g. via nasogastric tube) or parenteral (i.e. intravenous) administration. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral amoxicillin (aminopenicillin) and clavulanate (\u03b2-lactamase inhibitor)\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate treatment for this patient as it offers broad coverage of all relevant organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous benzylpenicillin and oral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is the typical treatment for moderate community acquired pneumonia (CAP).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E covers anaerobic infections which are unlikely in this case where aspiration has not occurred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous piperacillin-tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for high-severity HAP or those with high risk of MDR organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is key to note that this explanation is a general guide and it is crucial to check local guidelines or consult an infectious diseases clinician.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antibiotic regimens change frequently and guidelines are likely to vary between hospitals."],"references":["Rotstein C, Evans G, Born A, et al. Clinical practice guidelines for hospital-acquired pneumonia and ventilator-associated pneumonia in adults. Can J Infect Dis Med Microbiol. 2008;19(1):19-53.","Hospital-acquired pneumonia [published 2019 April]. In: eTG complete [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2020 Aug. \u003Chttps://www.tg.org.au\u003E","Eyler RF, Shvets K. Clinical Pharmacology of Antibiotics. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2019;14(7):1080-1090."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84425"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"9"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"i